subSubSection.paragraph:
Labrum uniformly shaped in both sexes (unique shape within subgen.
Microlepidia
), with arcuate basolateral margins, then conically attenuated towards acute or subacute anterolateral teeth and with prominent tridentate anteromedian lobe. Male labrum ( Figs 8–10 ) whitish-ivory to yellow except for pale brownish-testaceous median area and darkened limited basal area and margins of teeth, comparatively long, length 1.30–1.60 mm , width 1.45– 1.70 mm ; female labrum ( Fig. 11 ) usually darker, almost entirely brownish-testaceous, of the same shape as in male, yet somewhat longer, length 1.66–2.00 mm, width 1.65–2.10 mm , median tooth of prominently tridentate anteromedian lobe sometimes with blunt apex.

Mandibles (
Figs 3–5
) brown to reddish-brown except for paler basal area and blackened teeth, subsymmetrical, both mandibles with third tooth markedly smaller than other teeth.

Palpi. Maxillary palpi (
Fig. 7
) ochre-testaceous with terminal palpomeres usually brownish darkened in both sexes; labial palpi (
Fig. 6
) ochre to brownish-testaceous, usually darker in females; penultimate (longest) palpomeres of labial palpi elongate, slightly curved and moderately evenly inflated (width 
0.30–0.40 mm
), fringed with rows of testaceous setae.
